Feel Free is a movement to promote face-to -face interactions within local communities. It is focused on increasing face-to-face connections by utilizing existing collaborative venues as a platform to enhance communities. Feel Free has seamlessly combined three business platforms that will allow local businesses to promote themselves to their community on a highly personal level. I orchestrated a team of professionals to design, develop and implement a new idea into a functioning technological platform that combines social media and marketing, allowing businesses to more efficiently identify, market, and interact with their customers. ►►How it works and who it's for◄◄Feel Free makes communities stronger by making sure everyone talks to one another. We have created a mobile application that gives you the capability to see who else is in the coffee shop or other Feel Free space you're at so that you can then connect, communicate, and meet them should you desire to do so.This app shows you their names, what they do for a living, where they are from and the good things others have said about them. This helps you learn things about those around you so you can decide whether or not they are someone you want to meet. The app also allows the owners of the businesses to be able to communicate with you by letting you know of new events that are coming up, new products that just came out and even giving special discounts on products or services. This app is for anyone that wants to meet more people in their community. People that will use this are people that work for themselves or are able to work remotely. Business owners that will use this app own a coffee shop or co-working space that allows their customers to linger for long periods of time and have a desire to communicate more effectively with their patrons. To download the app, visit www.feelfreemovement.com

Architekton is the longest lasting architecture firm in the valley. I was recruited to support them on a large contract with Chase Bank doing tenant improvements for all branches in the southwest. During this time I gained valuable knowledge in construction documentation and working with a large corporate entity. I was also given the opportunity to design, develop and implement my design esthetics into courtrooms, public courtyards, recreation facilities, aquatics centers and multiple large-scale developments. My time at Architekton gave me the knowledge I needed in order to understand the inner workings of southwestern architectural firm. This has supported me tremendously as I continue to build my vision of the future of Phoenix.

Eventually this led to my obsession with community and collaboration.
